You can accomplish this without using any extra data structures by iterating through the two arrays and maintaining a set of unique elements. Here's an example in JavaScript:
```javascript
function findCommonElements(arr1, arr2) {
  let uniqueElements = new Set([
    ...arr1,
    ...arr2
  ]);

  let commonElements = [];

  for (let i = 0; i < arr1.length; i++) {
    for (let j = 0; j < arr2.length; j++) {
      const element = arr1[i] !== undefined ? arr1[i] : arr2[j];

      if (uniqueElements.has(element)) {
        commonElements.push(element);
      }
    }
  }

  return commonElements;
}

const arr1 = [1, 2, 3, 4];
const arr2 = [2, 3, 4, 5, 6];

console.log(findCommonElements(arr1, arr2)); // [2, 3, 4]
```
In this example, we use a `Set` to store the unique elements from both arrays. Then, we iterate through each array and check if the element is in the set. If it is, we push the element to the `commonElements` array.
